{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_echidna_ver01/data/sn82015425/00529040647/1948102901/0331.xml":{"full_text":"FRIDAY, OCTOBER 29, 1948\nLionel Hampton And Band-Show\nSet For City Auditorium Tonight\nTonight\u2019s the night when Ai\n-lan tan: will get the opportunity io\nsee and hear the illustrious instru\nmentalist Lionel Hampton and hi\ngreat, internationally famous or\nchestra after eight long years. The\nmaster presentation will be at Chy\nAuditorium from 1 p. m. to 3 a. m.\nAdvance indications Thursday\nwere that a large number of At\nlantans were moving to take ad\nvantage of the opportunity to see\nHamp who has broken every record\nof stage and ballroom and soared\nto topmost, heights in the swing\nmusic realm.\n\"Atlanta's tegrtrmate theatre\u2019*\nI f TOWER\nMX OFFICE OPEN DAILY I\nI I TO 8 P. M.\nrHfATM GUILD r No* <\u00bbt\nUTtONAL COMPANY a I 4 A\n(\u2022M m irno 6, OSCAR HAMMERSTEIN 24\nDwa b, ROUBEN MAMOULIAN\nI AGNES d. MiUf_\nSPECIAL SECTION RESERVED\nFOR COLORED\nNow on Sale at Box Office\nGENERAL ADMISSION\n$1.20\nAll Performances\nNovember Ist Thru 6th\nEvenings B:2G P. M.\nMet. Wed.-Fri.-Sat -2:20 P.M\npaodbeml\nHEIDELBERB BREWI G CO COVihgtom. by\nDistributed by\nASSOCIATED\nBEVERAGES CO.\n728 Humphries St., S. W.\nFaW GRAND\n5< and IO? STORE\nCO^N\u00a3RtVHITEHALL,HUNTEHandBnoAI)S7S.\nFRESH EGGS 59\u00b0\nCampbell's\nTOMATO\nSOUP\n10 c\n2!2 Russell\nPEACHES\n19 c\nAGED, STRONG\nCHEESE 63 c cSe 49 c\nColored\nChurngold\nOLEG\n45 c lb.\nPrize of Albany\nSAUSAGE\n43 c\nBABY FOODS S 3 -29 c\nARMOUR\u2019S\nMILK\n3 tall 41 c\n31-OZ. CAN\nARMOUR\u2019S\nPORK AND\nBEANS\n19 c\nLocal King And\nQueen Of Blues\nSought In Contest\nThe band-show presentation by\nHim pion lias been heralded coast\nto-coast as one of the most en\ntertaining spectacles on the circuits\ntoday.\nIn addition, Atlantans who sing\nthe Blues will have the opportun\nity to compete in Hampton's \u201cMr.\no- Miss Blues Contest.\" The win\nners will recive cash prizes and an\nengagement with Hampton's or\nchestra.\nAtlantans will remember \u201cThe\nGreat Hamp\" as a former member\nof the famed Benny Goodman\nQuartet, the recordings of which\nare jazz classics. Few musicians on\nthe American scene today are more\n'Deep South Boys'\nTo Appear At\nCentenary Church\nThe Board of Trustees of Cen\ntenary Methodist church will pre\nsent The Deep South Boy's Quar\ntet Sunday, October 31, at 7:30 p.\nm. These young men, under the\ndirection of Mr. Sims Gordon, are\nno strangers to Atlanta. They are\nColumbia recording artists and are\nheard over radio station WGST ev\nery Sunday morning. Admission\n35 cents.\nMr. Charles Lucas is chairman of\nthe Board of Trustees. Rev. E. A.\nBaldridge, pastor.\nLet The Good\nTimes Roll\nB AKMOt ILS^S\nCORNED\n[mutton]\nI Just Try It. Is All I\nA We Ask\u2014l2-Oz. Can\n1^37^1\nFLA.\nFRESH JUICY\nORANGES\nLarge She\n^2s^\nIn Our\nBakery Dept.\nBF Goblin Spec.\nf CHIFFON 1\nCAKES\nHalloween Colors I\nL 79 c and J|\nsj[o9\noutstanding than the members of\nthe Quartet--Benny Goodman, the\n\u25a0cc clarinetist: Gene Krupa.\u2019 the\ndrummer; Teddy Wilson the stel\nlar pianist, and Lionel Hampton\nthe world's greatest vibraharpist:\nHampton plays with mastery, in\naddition, the drums and the piano,\nsome of his recordings with these\ninstruments being jazz classics. His\nband of outstanding showmen-mu\nsicians features everything in jazz\nand sets a new tempo for world\nartists. He promises to put a new\ntwist to \"Hamp's Boogie.\" the rec\nord -classic tonight.\nHampton\u2019s show, acclaimed as\n\"terrific,\" includes Red and Cur\nley, the famed Broadway show-top\npers, and Roland Burton, singer.\nTickets for the engagement are\nselling at $1.50 advance and $2 at\nthe door. Advance ducats will re\nmain on sale through 9 o'clock to\nnight. Southeastern Artists co\nordinates.\nTurner Monumental\nSet For Musical\nThe choirs and choruses of Tur\nner Monumental AME church will\npresent a joint musical tonight at\n8 p. m. with approximately one hun\ndred voices. Mrs. Jessie J. Rudolph\nwill sing choice numbers requested\nby friends. The public is invited.\nThere will be no admission. A bask\net of groceries and a five dollar bill\nwill be given as prizes.\nSunday at 11 a. in. Rev. H. John\nson will deliver the morning mes\nsage. At 3:30 p. m. Rev. Wm. P.\nKing, pastor, Shiloh Baptist church,\nwill bring the message. Sunday is\ndollar money day. Class leaders\nand members will report for dollar\nmoney. The public is invited to wor\nship with us.\nOddities Harrass\nPostal Employe\nGuy Broughton, employee of the\nPost Office, has had some strange\nthings happen to him.\nLast year Broughton found a\npoisonous snake coiled under a\npackage in the mail room.\nThe latest happening appears to\nbe almost as unusual.\nThe employe said forthree days\nhe noticed soot falling out ot his\nchimney at 201 Randolph St., N E.\nand in cleaning it out discovered a\npigeon had been trapped iuside.\nBroughton said he freed the\nbird and Wednesday it appeared\non the road to recovery.\nPERSONALS\nMRS. LAVONIA MITCHELL of\n89 Bell St. SE\u201e Apt. 75 left the city\nWednesday evening for New York\nCity on business.\nDeaths\nANDERSON. Mrs. Mamie of Sa\nvannah. Ga., passed at a local hos\npital.\nMIZE, Mr. Martin of near Ma\nrietta passed at the residence.\nHEARD. Mr. Anuderson D. pass\ned at his residence, Thomasville,\nOctober 27.\nMILLER. Mrs. Leola Taylor of 91\nHill Top Circle, Apt. 531 passed at\nher residence October 27.\nHOLLOMON, Mrs. Octavia of\n135 Mulberry St., passed away ar\nher residence.\nOhio Gets First\nNew Car Dealer\nCLEVELAND\u2014 ANP \u2014The state\nof Ohio had its frist Negro new\ncar dealer last week when Robert\nL. Carter was awarded a franchise\nto sell Kaiser- Frazier automobiles\nat his display rooms at 10107 Ce\ndar Avenue.\nDuring the past 12 years Carter\nhas operated an auto repair shop\nand used car sale room at this lo\ncation. G. P Hutchins is sales\nmanager of the firm, and Clarence\nCarter is a salesman.\n\"The business outlook for Negroes\nin this fieltV Carter said \u201chas\ngreatly increased. This is because of\nthe growing interest, ability and\ninitiative of Negroes.\u201d\nSpeaking of his relationships\nwith the white dirtributors of Kai\nzer-Frazier cars. Carter commented.\n\"Relationships with the local dis\ntributors, Raymond-Lake. Inc., have\nbeen only the best. Through them\nthe franchise was obtained, and\nthey were particularly anxious to\nsee us get off to a good start in a\nnew field.\n\"We also received full and helpful\ncooperation with Associates Invest\nment corp., who will handle our\nwholesale and retail financing.\u201d\nCALL\nAMherst\n4021\nNo. 2 Van Camp\u2019s\nHOMINY\n10 c\n5-Lb. Bag\nCORN\nMEAL\n29 c\n3-Lb. Ctn.\nJEWEL\nShortening\n_B9^_\nWICKLOW\nSLICED\nBACON\n59 c\nBLACK\nPEPPER\n10 c\n2*2 CAN\nAPRICOTS\n2 fw 25 c\nTonight! Hear\nCharles P.\nHOWARD\nDistinguished Negro Leader from\nlowa and Keynote Speaker\nat founding Convention speak\non the\nWALLACE\nPROGRAM\nTONIGHT\u2014B:OO P. M.\nIst. CONG. CHURCH\nCourtland Houston Sts.\nPEOPLES' PROGRESSIVE\nPARTY\nATLANTA DAILY WORLD, ATLANTA, GEORGIA\nIT\u2019S \u2019\u2019BOB-LE -BOB\u201d TONITE 11 P. M. AUDITORIUM\n9 Hl II\n1 wB i\u2122 ^lfl RS h S\n--W Bl 9e^k pS 11H\nB 1\u00ae! rl ot\nI f I Wd 1 fin\nL s rI li\n11L u wft tsk s' JI 11 IL.-\u00ab\nLionel HAA^PTON Greatest Bandleader-Showman, brings the greatest musicrew and Broad\nway acts ever assembled in one unit-package tonite, Friday, i 1 P. M. at the Auditorium. Ad\nvance\u2014sl.so; at Box\u2014s2.oo. Tickets available now at ail locations until 8 p. m. Co-ordina\ntors\u2014S. E. Artists.\nFrank B. Adair Goes To\nNorth Carolina Hospital\nNEW YORK Frank B. Adair.\nAssistant Executive Director oi\nSydenham Hospital, has accepted\nthe appointment of Administrator\n>t the Community Hospital, Wil\nmington, North Carolina it was an\nncunced this week. Mr. Adair came\nto Sydenham three years ago as\nAdministrative Intern, receiving \u2018he\nfust appointment of its kind, grant\ned a Negro in voluntary hospitals\nmywhere in the United States.\nSubsequently, upon the re.^igna\n\u2022ion of S. L. Friedman. M. D., as\nExecutive Director of the Hospital\nChristian Advocate, official of the\nMr. Adair was named Acting Exe\ncutive Director, pending the ap\npointment of a medical admini-\nstrator.\nMr. Adan, -an antmmis of More\nhouse College, did his postgraduate\nwork al the Harvard University\nGraduate School of Business Ad\nministration. He is a member of;\nthe American Hospital A-sociation.\nand holds certificates in Hospital\nAdministration from the American\nCollege of Hospital Admmi.-tra' >rs\nand in hospital purcha.-ing from\nthe American Hospital A ociation.\nHe served as honorary vice-Presi- i\ndent of the Committee on Private\nHospitals of the New York Cancer\nCcmmittee and is a member of the i\nNew York Harvard Business School\nClub. Before coming to New York i\nj he served as Business Manager of\nDillard University and a- Adtmni\nstrative Officer at Tuskegee Insti\ntute.\nIn accepting the new appointment I\nMr. Adair said that he did so\n\u201cwith a great deal ot reluctance.\nfeeling as I do about Sydenham\nWANTED\nEXPERIENCED OPERATOR\nTo Rent Booth\nHazel's Beauty Shop\n250 AUBURN AVENUE, N. E\nCY. 9807\nIncrease\nYear Com fart flflH\nEnhance y^/flflfl\nAppearance nfl|^|\nt\u2014JEn\nWear BUHL'S Fashion Styled\nGLASSES\nAttractive Frames\nWith Any Strength\nQuality Lenses\nComplete\nSingle or Double Vision\nK \u00bb1\u201cj J MbK Ki ii, Clear\nBV QSM\nOPTICAL CO.\n4 Peachtree St.\nHospital and the ideals which it\nlias advanced. However. I accept\n:lit North Carolina appointment as\nboth a challenge and an opportun\ni;y I am eager to put into opera\ntion. in a hospital under my own\ndi\u2019r, am. many of the precedures\nand ideals with which it has\nbeen my pood fortune to collabo\nrate at Sydenham Hospital during\nliu past three yars.\"\nFRANK f.- ADAIR\n1\nGiv^F\njive\nnough t\n'Neal Says You'll\nNever See Anything\nBetter Of Its Kind'\nLionel ifumpn n. t King of the I\nVibes, ace drummer man. and wiz- 1\naid on the piano, brings his inflam-\nmable dance band and Show-stop\nping acts tonight. 11 p. m. to 3 a.\nm. to the auditorium.\nThe great \"Hamp\", as he is af\nfectionately called, returns to At\nlanta after a period of 8 long years\nto play his first post war date, and\nit appear: it is going to be one of\nI smash proportions in attendance,\njudging by the talk heard in every\nportion of the town.\nLasted high on the format of en\ntertainment will be Roland Burton,\nsinger of sentimental songs. Red\n.and Curly dancing comics and oth\ner Broadway personalities.\nI The Hampton entourage will ar-\nI rive early today from Greenville, S.\nC and \u25a0'Hampton\", after a brief\nrest, will be guested on practically\n.all radio stations, where \"Bop\u201d is.\nrecognized and certified.\nI Since there is a previous attrac- i\ni tion at the auditorium patrons are\nrequested not to come before 10:45\nip. m Doors will open as soon as\nj practicable thereafter. Advance\ni ticket, will be available until 8 p\n|m. at all locations. Southeastern\nj Artists Co-ordinates.\nI Powell To 'Tell\nAll' In Broadcast\nj NEW YORK ANP< Congress\nman A Clayton Powell announced\nthis week that he would \"tell every\nthing\u201d over radio station WMCA\nSunday afternoon. October 31.\nRev. Powell, who has occasional\nly been critized for not champai\n\u25a0..ning against his Republican op\nponent, Harold C Burton, has been\ntelling friends:\n\u201cThere's nothing to campaign\nabout. nobodv to campaign\nagainst.\u201d\nAltliou :i tie is a Democrat,\nPowell has yet to deciare for Presi\no\u2019ent Truman.\nH. D. Kittinger Co.\n47 Whitehall St.\nThree Doors From Alabama St.\nAIR CONDITIONED GROCERY and MEAT DEPT.\nFRIDAY and SATURDAY\nMONEY-SAVING VALUES\nPEANUT BUTTER 27\u2018\nNo. 1 Can Untea\nSftLMON.. 34\u2019\n7-Oz. Box Dried\nSKIM MILK 15\n1 Lb., 8-Oz, Can Wilson's\nTRIPE... 49 c\nl? Oz. Kinsan\u2019s\nK.P. Lunch Meat 47 c\nVEGETABLE SOUP 6 C\nDaisy Cheese 41 c\n5-Lb. Bag\nSUGAR 42 c\nTop Wave Flake\nTUNAFISH^36 C\nSliced\nBOLOGNA >4f\nALL SOUTHERN\nOLEO MARGARINE 28\u00b0 I\nAlabama Methodists\nIn Annual Meeting\nBy REV. JOEL C. ARSON\nThe Central Alabama Annual;\nConference of th e Methodist\nChurch was in session with the\nGoodsei Memorial church in Lan\nett, Alabama. Wednesdav of last\nweek Oct. 13-17. Bishop J. W. E.\nBowen of the Atlantic Coast\nArea, presided. Rev. G. W. Brown\nwas host pastor and Rev. L. G\nFields wa> host District Superin\ntendent. Rev. O. R. Flournoy was\nelected secretary and Rev. L H\nZeigler, Dr. R. C. Hatch and Rev\nLeon Kennedy was elected assist\nant secretaries. Rev. J. C Wilson\nv.as elected Statistical Secretary.\nBishop Bowen was interested in\nevery minor derail of the confer\nence and was careful to see that\nevery Board. Commission and Com\nmictee was properly organized and\ninformed of its duty.\n\"Faith m God\" was the tuple of\ntia Bishop's Communion Address,\nand the \"Advance' program of the\nchurch was kept before the con\nference throughout the session. A\nSeminar on the \"Advance for\nChrist and nis Church\u201d was led by\nRevs. L. G. Field-. T H Houston\nand Mr. L. W. Lynn. Sermons were\npreached on \"Our Faith in Christ\nby Rev. J B F. Williams and \"Our\nFaith in the Kingdom of God\" by\nRev. W L. Turner. Bishop Bowen\nadequately covered the quadren\ni nial program m ms >erm -a x;im\nday morning..\nA local program of Welcome to\nthe delegation was given on Wed\nnesday evening, presided over by\nProf. Bryant. Principal of the city\nhigh school. Both raves took part\nin this program and the writer re\n.-ponded on behalf of the confer\nence.\nOther inspirational <ermons were\npreached by Brothers O. R. Fioui\nnoy. G H. Holman and Dr. J. II\nBurgess. The Conference was sad\ndened bv the deaths during the\nyear of Rev.-. P. P. Wright, G W\nWashington. T. H Ham. 3 L. D\nKnox and A. R. Matthews lae w;s\nter delivered the Memorial address\nBrothers Douglas I. Kirk and Jo\nE Lowery were admitted, and\nBrothers Benjamin N Smith. J. H.\nPuter, O. W. Gibson and O. J\nLeath were admitted into full con i\nnoct ion. Sister Josephine Saunders\nand Bro. Oliver W. Gibson were\nordained deacons and Brother- Ben\njamin Johnson. Benjamin Smith,\nMajor Lewis, and J. H. Puter were\nordained elders. Revs. J. H. Duf- I\nfie. D D Vann and J. H Gilder\nwere granted retired relation- at\ntheir own request. The conference\nwas graced with the presence of\nmany\" visitors among whom were\nMiss Skinner of the Board of Edu\ncation. Dr. Brawley. President of\nCLrk College, Dr. Seabrook, pres\nitient of Claflin College, Reverend\nTi.omas. Prof, at Gammon Theo-\nCountry Man In Town\nSponsored by the\nUsher Board\nNOVEMBER 5, 1948-8:00\nPINEY GROVE BAPTIST\nCHURCH\nPrice 25c tax ind.\n12-Oz. Buiua. Pure\nAPPLE JELLY 14\nLLb. Drip or Regular\nSupreme Coffee 49 c\nTall Can Armour's Evaporated\nMILK .2 27 c\n24\u20145 c Plain or Almond\nHERSHEY BARS 97 c\n2-Lb. Ctn.\nPURE LARD 49 c\nPrize of Albany\nSAUSAGE 43 c\nBoneless Roll\nYEAL BOAST -65\u2018\nFftT BACK24'\nPAGE THREE\nlogical Seminary, Drs. Howard.\nGolden, D. H. Stanton, Stinson. E.\nW. McMillan, J. A. Baxter, Thoma\nand many others. Dr. R. H. McAl\nlister of the Advocate and the\nMethodist Publishing Hou\u00bbe report\ned the largest number of subscrip\ntions ever given to the Central\nAdvocate by this Conference <B6O\nand all of hi- book brought to the\nconference were sold. Bishop Bow\nens Christian manner and inethod.-\nendeared him to the conference\nand every man went to his charge\ninspired to do a greater work. Rev\nJ. B. F. Williams was appointed\nSrperintendent of the Opelika D:\ntrict The conference adjourned on\nSunday afternoon to meet in Mon:\ngomery in 1949.\nA full list of the appointments\nwill be released at a later date.\nSome of the major appointments\non the Birmingham District are:\nSt. Paul. Rev. H. B. Gibson; Enon\nMethodist, Rev. C. J. Booker; St.\nJames. East Thomas. Reverent!\nJoseph Lowery; Mount Moriah.\nRev A. .T Jones; W-iglt's Chapel\nRev. W. Gates; Rev. O. Gibson,\nWarrior; Rev. Marcus. Village\nSpring-; Rev Springer, Sareyton\nRev. J J Harrison is Superintend\nent of the Birmingham District.\nDr Y. L Brown was relected Con\nference Lay leader\nOther Superintendent.- are: Rev.\nt 11. Houston of the Huntsville\nDistrict; Rev. W. L Langford of\n\u2022he Mobile District; Rev. J. Whit\nfield of the Montgomery District,\nand Rev J B. F. Williams of the\nOpelika District\nCitizens Democratic\nClub Meets Tonite\nA special meeting of the execu\ntive committee of the Citizens\nDemocratic club of Fulton county\nwill be held thr- evening at t\u2019m-\nButler Street YMCA at 7 o'clock\npromptly. The meeting will consid\ner important matters relative to\nthe approaching elections on Tues\nday November 2.\nSPECIALS\nTHIS WEEK AT\nSILVER\u2019S\nGROCERY DEPT.\nWE HAVE A\nCOMPLETE\nSTOCK OF FRUIT\nCAKE INGREDIENTS\nLarge B Fresh\nEGGS ooz 59 c\nCured\nPORK CHOPS u 59 e\nAged\nHOOP CHEESEu 49\nKingan's Indiana\nVIENNA SAUSAGE 2 ^25 c\nLarge Juicy\nORANGES 25\u00b0\n^^STKEAK^^\nO\u2019 LEAN\nr ib 24c\nHOCKtESS 1\nI\u2019H NIC\nI lB 49c\nA PURE LARD\n|L4 is. CTN 99cJ|\nNo. 2 Can\nTOMATOES 2 c 25\u00b0\nJackson No. 1 Can\nVEG.SOUP 6\u00b0\nNo. 1 Tall\nSALMON 59\u00b0\n5-Lb. Bag\nGRITS 39\u00b0\n5-Lb. Bag\nMEAL m 29\nBALLARD'S or CAPITOLA\nFLOUR\n25-lb. ba6 2.19\n10-LB. BAG 35\u00b0\nSILVER'S\nsc4Qc-$1 STORE\n117 Whitehall SK\ni","height":"25512","width":"20604"}}
